{# Philosophy Section #}
<div class="section-isolate" data-section-name="philosophy" data-section-type="content">
  <div class="container">
    <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="philosophy-title">
      <h2 id="philosophy-title" class="section-title">📖 The Philosophy</h2>
      <h3 class="section-subtitle">EverydayAI: Learning from History</h3>
      
      <p class="lead" style="text-align: center; max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto 2rem;">
        My book <strong>"EverydayAI"</strong> (coming 2026) argues that we must learn from everyday technological transitions in history—the printing press, the industrial revolution, the internet—to understand where we are in history and make the AI transition work for everyone.
      </p>

      <div class="three-col-grid">
        <div class="history-card">
          <div class="history-icon">📜</div>
          <h4>The Printing Press</h4>
          <p>Democratized knowledge but created massive displacement of scribes. Access to education determined who thrived in the new era.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="history-card">
          <div class="history-icon">⚙️</div>
          <h4>Industrial Revolution</h4>
          <p>Increased productivity dramatically but created inequality. The Luddites weren't anti-technology—they wanted fair access to opportunity.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="history-card">
          <div class="history-icon">🌐</div>
          <h4>The Internet</h4>
          <p>Connected the world but left communities behind. The digital divide wasn't about technology—it was about coordination and access.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-box callout-emphasis" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <p class="lead"><strong>AI is the same pattern, but faster.</strong> We can either repeat history's mistakes and let AI create massive inequality, or we can intentionally build something inclusive from day one.</p>
        <p class="lead" style="margin-top: 1rem;">The choice isn't whether AI transforms our economy. The choice is whether we coordinate to ensure everyone has access to the opportunity.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</div>

